Malawi Tea Price Rises 14% in a Week on Increased Demand

-- B y   F r a n k   J o m o
-- 
2011-07-12T15:18:52Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-12/malawi-tea-price-rises-14-in-a-week-on-increased-demand-1-.html
The benchmark price of tea in
 Malawi ,  Africa ’s largest producer of the crop after Kenya,
gained 14 percent at auction today on strong demand for the
better grades, according to Tea Brokers Central Africa, which
manages the country’s tea sales.  The top grade of tea, known as pekoe fannings, sold for
$2.88 a kilogram (2.2 pounds) at a sale in the commercial
capital, Blantyre, up from $2.53 a week ago, Tea Brokers said in
an e-mailed report.  Farmers raised $294,106 selling 163,460 kilograms of
various grades of tea, compared with $129,873 from 94,880
kilograms a week earlier, it said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Frank Jomo in Blantyre via Johannesburg at 
 fjomo@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Antony Sguazzin at 
 asguazzin@bloomberg.net  